"&#xa0;\nAFS0068&#xa0;Written evidence submitted by NASUWT &#xa0;\nThe \nNASUWT\n’s submission sets out the Union’s views on the key issues identified by the Committee in the terms of reference for the Inquiry \nThe evidence is informed by\n the work of its representative committees and \nconsultative structures made up of practis\ning teacher\ns and\n school leaders\n working in the \neducation system in England.\n&#xa0;\nThe NASUWT is the largest union representing teachers and headteachers in the \nUK\n.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;Executive Summary&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Background and context&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe Coalition Government’s academies and free schools programmes&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\ni) Equality of opportunity – \nReform programmes must seek to promote the development of an education system \nthat \nensures\n equality of opportunity in terms of admissions, provision and \neducational outcomes.\n&#xa0;\nii) Democratic accountability – R\neform of the\n education system\n must be consistent with democratic values and must ensure that all publicly funded institutions are democratically accountable to the communities \nthey serve\n.\n&#xa0;\niii) Value for money/transparency – \nReform strategies must seek to \nsecure effective\n transparency in \nrelation to the way in which financial resources are allocated across the system\n and should ensure that all spending commitments \nare\n \nevaluated robustly and objectively against clear economic efficiency and value for money c\nriteria.\n&#xa0;\niv) Raises standards – \nR\neforms of the school system must be designed to ensure that \nall pupils are able to access high quality, engaging and relevant leaning opportunities\n that secure the highest possible levels of pupil progress and achievement\n.\n&#xa0;\nv) Union recognition – \nApproaches to reform must \nensure that workforce unions a\nre properly represented to enable \nthe perspectives of teachers, school leaders and other members of the wider school workforce \nto be \ntaken into effective account\n \nin strategic planning and decision-making processes \nand \nto ensure that \ncondition\ns are created that support and promote \nhigh quality teaching and learning\n.\n&#xa0;\nvi) National \npay and conditions of service –\n \nReform programmes \nmust support \nthe operation of \nnationa\nl pay and conditions\n frameworks that ensure that all pupils, regardless of the school they attend, \nreceive their \ncommon \nentitlement to \nhighly skilled, \nmotivated and well trained teacher\ns\n \nwith \nterms and conditions \nthat enable them to work effectively to rai\nse standards.\n&#xa0;\nvii) Viability – \nApproaches to reform must\n ensure that all \nschools and other relevant settings\n are viable and sustainable financially and are not \nfunded on the basis of\n sectional or individual short term interests.\n&#xa0;\nviii) \nA s\nupportive and co\nllaborative approach to community education – \nReform programmes must secure\n \nthe adoption and enhancement of \ncollaborati\nve approaches within and between \ninstitutions\n, noting, however, that collaboration does not preclude parents from exercising \ntheir legiti\nmate \nrights to make \ninformed \nchoices about the \nschools or other relevant settings their children might attend.\n&#xa0;\nix) Rooted within the community – \nAny reform of the education system \nmust ensure that schools are rooted within, not set apart from,\n their commu\nnities\n and represent the best of the values and aspirations of \nthose\n communities\n.\n&#xa0;\nx) Evidence based – \nApproaches to reform\n must be based on a genuine, considered use of evidence of educational practice, building on consultation betwe\nen all stakeholders, \ni\nncluding workforce\n unions.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nEducational progress and achievement in the academies and free school sectors&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\nThe process for establishing free schools and academies&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\nThe alternatives to sponsored academy status that might be offered to primary schools perceived as underperforming&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDecember 2013\n&#xa0;\n15\n NASUWT (2013). \nMaintaining World Class Schools\n. NASUWT; \nBirmingham\n.\n Department for Education (2013). ‘Sponsored academies improvement in GCSEs outstripping other schools’ \nGov.uk. \n(\n24 January\n).\n \n(\nhttps://www.g\nov.uk/government/news/sponsored-academies-improvement-in-gcses-outstripping-other-schools\n), accessed on 08/12/13.\n Stewart, H. (2013). ‘The academies illusion: what the data reveals.’ \nLocal Schools Network.\n (30 May) (\nhttp://www.localschoolsnetwork.org.uk/2013/05/the-academies-illusion-what-the-data-reveals/\n), accessed on 08/12/13.\n National Audit Office (NAO) (2012). \nManaging the expansion of the\n academies programme\n. \nTSO; \nLondon\n.\n BBC News (2013). ‘Tories reject Nick Clegg’s free school comments’. \nBBC News\n 20 October. (\nhttp://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24604199\n), accessed on 09/12\n/13.\n Keilos, K. (2013). ‘Free schools shake the Swedish model’. \nPolicy Network. \n22 November. (\nhttp://www.policy-network.net/pno_detail.aspx?ID=\n4530&amp;title=-Free-schools-shake-the-Swedish-Model\n), accessed on 09/12/13.\n Pollard, N. (2103) ‘Insight – \nSweden\n rethinks pioneering school reforms, private equity under fire’ \nReuters. \n(10 December) (\nhttp://uk.mobile.reuters.com/article/idUKBRE9B905720131210?irpc=932\n), accessed on 10/12/13.\n Simon, S. (2013). \n‘Charter schools offer scant edge over neighborhood schools: study’\n \nReuters\n \n(25 June). (\nhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2013/